WSS (Wearable Stimulation System)

WSS is a modular and programmable system for delivering Functional Electrical Stimulation (FES) using dry active electrodes. The system consists of a gray stimulation unit (main device), electrode cables, and a gold control unit for wireless operation.

1. Gray Box Main Stimulation Unit

The gray box is the core of the system. It has multiple labeled faces, each with distinct functionality.

Face A Output Panel

Figure 1. Output panel with labeled connectors 14.

This panel contains two output ports, each with two internal connectors.

  • Port shape: asymmetric rectangle (one edge straight, one edge curved)
  • Total of 4 pin connectors:
    • Left port: pins 4 and 3
    • Right port: pins 2 and 1
  • Connects to the main stimulation cable via a keyhole connector

Face B Type-C and LED Panel

Figure 2. Rear panel with USB-C and two LED rows (labeled 17).

This panel includes two horizontal rows, each with functional components labeled in the image above:

Top Row (Labels 13):

  • (1) USB Type-C port used for charging the gray box
  • (2) Green LED turns on when charging is in progress
  • (3) Red LED turns on when charging is complete

Bottom Row (Labels 47):

  • (4) Green LED indicates the device is powered on
  • (5, 6, 7) Yellow LEDs programmable indicators for user-defined feedback (e.g., command status, stimulation phase, debug info)

Charging requires a 5V power adapter and only functions when the mode switch is set to Charging.

Face C 3-Way Power Mode Switch

Figure 3.Side panel with 3-way power mode switch labeled with three positions

The device is controlled by a three-position switch:

  • (1) On : enables full operation, receives and executes radio commands
  • (2) Off: device completely powered off
  • (3) Charging: enables battery charging; program logic disabled

The device will not charge unless the switch is in Charging mode. The device will not run any programs in Charging mode.

Audio Feedback

The gray box provides internal audio cues:

  • On sound: device successfully powered on
  • Start sound: stimulation started
  • End sound: stimulation completed
  • Warning sound: error occurred, device requires reboot

2. Cable and Electrode System

Main Stimulation Cable

The main stimulation cable connects the gray box (WSS output port) to the blue electrode adapter cable. It transmits the stimulation current via two independent wireseach corresponding to one output channel (positive and negative).

Keyhole Connector Overview


Figure 4. Keyhole connector interface used to connect to the output port of the gray box.

The gray box features keyhole-shaped output ports, each with two internal contacts. The stimulation cable plugs into one of these ports via a precisely shaped connector that ensures correct alignment.

  • Each port accepts one keyhole connector
  • Each connector contains two holes, which correspond to the positive (+) and negative () terminals

Cable End Overview

Figure 5. Top-down view of both ends of the stimulation cable: keyhole connector (left) and 2mm touchproof connector (right).

  • The keyhole connector end plugs into the gray box
  • The 2mm touchproof plugs on the other end connect to the blue adapter cable

Each internal wire from the keyhole connector is routed to a separate 2mm touchproof connector.

Polarity Identification

Figure 6. Keyhole connector showing white polarity marker on the cable jacket. This indicates the positive (+) side.

To distinguish polarity:

  • The cable wire with a white square label wrapped around the jacket corresponds to the positive (+) terminal
  • The other wire, without a marker, is the negative () terminal

Blue Electrode Adapter Cable

Figure 7. Blue adapter cable with touchproof input and snap connector output.

  • Connects from 2mm touchproof to the dry electrode

Dry Active Electrode and ACE Ring (HFI only)

The dry active electrode is a reusable stimulation interface. It is mounted on an ACE ring to ensure repeatable finger placement.

Electrode Overview

Figure 8. Dry active electrode front view.

This is a reusable electrode with a metallic conductive face. It connects via snap socket and is designed for contact on the skin.

Electrode Side Structure


Figure 9. Dry electrode side-view showing mounting groove.

A side groove is present along the base, designed to slide into the elastic track of the ACE ring.

Electrode Embedded in ACE Ring

Figure 10. Dry electrode mounted into ACE ring track.

The ACE ring consists of two elastic bands forming a guide rail for the electrode. The electrode snaps in and holds steadily against the finger.

Finger Mounting Demonstration

Figure 11. Dry electrode worn on finger: back view (left) and palm view (right).

3. Gold Control Box Wireless Command Sender

Each gold box serves as a wireless controller that communicates with a specific gray box. Communication is established via radio, and pairing is fixed one-to-one based on labeled ID.

Figure 12. Gold control box. Left: full view (with labeled pairing ID); center: Micro-USB-C interface side; right: alternate viewing angle.

The gold box is a rectangular controller designed to send serial commands to the gray box wirelessly. It connects to a PC via a Micro-USB-C interface and is identified by a unique ID printed on a label at the bottom of the unit.

  • Communication: One-to-one pairing with gray box, fixed via matching ID label
  • Connection to PC: Micro-USB-C port (visible on the narrow side)

Each gold box is dedicated to a specific gray box. The matching ID can be found on the bottom label of each unit.

4. Stimulation Execution Sequence

  1. Power on the gray box (On sound plays)
  2. Transmit commands via gold box (commands are received but no output yet)
  3. Send Start signal (Start sound plays)
    • The gray box begins executing the programmed stimulation commands
  4. Execution ends automatically or on End command (End sound plays)

The device will not output current until the Start signal is received. If a Warning sound plays, stimulation is halted and a reboot is required.

System Summary

  • Gray box: receives wireless commands and outputs stimulation current
  • Gold box: sends commands via radio, connects to PC via USB
  • Main cable: connects gray box to blue adapter
  • Blue adapter: connects to electrode
  • Electrode + ACE ring: delivers current to finger
  • LEDs and buzzer: indicate system status

WSS Commands Structure

This document defines the commands and procedures for communicating with WSS (Wireless Surface Stimulator) devices via serial USB communication.

1. Search and Identify the Connected WSS units

Connect the wireless receiver to the USB port of your computer

Mac OS:

Open a terminal app,

In order to list all serial ports, use:

ls /dev/tty.*

To filter only USB-Serial devices

ls /dev/tty.usbserial*

Look for device names like /dev/tty.usbserial-AB0XXXXX which identify WSS units. The serial number (e.g., AB0OD22E) is embedded in the device name.

Configure the Serial Port

In terminal use the command below to configure the serial port as follows.

  • Baud Rate: 115200
  • Data Bits: 8
  • Stop Bits: 1
  • Parity: None
  • Flow Control: None
stty -f /dev/tty.usbserial-AB0XXXXX 115200 cs8 -cstopb -parenb -ixon -crtscts

Replace AB0XXXXX with your devices code.

Windows

2. Send and Receive Commands

Echo Request Message

00 81 07 02 12 AB B7 C0
Byte Description
00 Host Address
81 WSS Device Address
07 Command ID (ECHO)
02 Payload Length
12 AB Data Payload
B7 Checksum
C0 End Byte

The Echo command tells the WSS to send the same payload back to the sender, helping confirm that communication is working correctly.

Send message

MacOS:

echo "00 81 07 02 12 AB B7 C0" | xxd -r -p > echo_msg.bin
cat echo_msg.bin > /dev/tty.usbserial-AB0XXXXX

This will save the command bits to a file named echo_msg.bin and transfer it to specified USB device.

Windows:

TBD

Read response

MacOS

In order to receive a message from your WSS device, open a new terminal window and enter

cat /dev/tty.usbserial-AB0XXXXX

Use the code below in order to convert received message to hex format.

cat /dev/tty.usbserial-AB0XXXXX | xxd

Structure of received message

You might receive a message as shown below:

00 81 07 02 12 AB B7 C0

Here is the breakdown for this message:

Byte(s) Description
81 Sender address (WSS target address)
00 Receiver address (host PC)
07 Command code ECHO command
02 Payload length 2 bytes
12 AB Payload Echo data (should match what was sent)
B7 Checksum Verifies message integrity
C0 End byte Marks the end of the message

You should be receiving the same data payload, which is 12 AB.

MATLAB Example:

Works the same on macOS and Windowsjust change the port name.

port = '/dev/tty.usbserial-AB0OD22E';  % Or a 'COM' port on Windows. Replace AB0OD22E with your device address

s = serialport(port, 115200, ...
    'DataBits', 8, ...
    'Parity', 'none', ...
    'StopBits', 1, ...
    'FlowControl', 'none');

msg = uint8([0x00, 0x81, 0x07, 0x02, 0x12, 0xAB, 0xB7, 0xC0]);
write(s, msg, "uint8");
pause(0.1);

if s.NumBytesAvailable > 0
    response = read(s, s.NumBytesAvailable, "uint8");
    disp("Received:");
    disp(response);
end

Notes

  • On macOS, you may need to grant terminal or MATLAB access under System Settings Privacy & Security Developer Tools.
  • Always verify the correct port and serial number.
  • Use only one program per port at a time.

3. WSS Command List

1. Reset Command (0x04)

Example

00 81 04 00 7A C0
Byte Description
00 Host Address
81 WSS Device Address
04 Command ID (RESET)
00 Payload Length
7A Checksum
C0 End Byte

The Reset command instructs the WSS device to perform a software reset, clearing any temporary configurations or errors, and restoring the device.

Use this command if:

  • The WSS becomes unresponsive.
  • You want to reset device before reprogramming it for your use case.

2. Echo Request Command (0x07)

Example

00 81 07 02 12 AB B7 C0
Byte Description
00 Host Address
81 WSS Device Address
07 Command ID (ECHO)
02 Payload Length (2 bytes)
12 AB Data Payload
B7 Checksum
C0 End Byte

The Echo Request command is used to verify communication between the host and the WSS device. When the WSS receives this command, it sends back the same data payload (12 AB) to the host. This helps confirm that the device is powered on, correctly connected, and capable of receiving and transmitting messages.

It is commonly used for debugging serial communication or validating correct device response behavior.

3. Analog Request Command (0x02)

Example

00 81 02 01 01 7A C0
Byte Description
00 Host Address
81 WSS Device Address
02 Command ID (ANALOG REQUEST)
01 Payload Length (1 byte)
01 Subcommand (Request analog data)
7A Checksum
C0 End Byte

The Analog Request command is used to retrieve analog measurements from the WSS device. When sent with subcommand 01, the device responds with values such as:

  • Battery voltage
  • Electrode impedance

This command is typically used during diagnostics, setup, or system monitoring to ensure signal quality and sufficient power levels before starting operation.

4. Clear Configuration Command (0x40)

The Clear Configuration command instructs the WSS device to reset its internal memory related to contacts, scheduled events, and schedules. The specific target of the reset is determined by a single-byte subcommand.

Example

00 81 40 01 00 3D C0
Byte Description
00 Host Address
81 WSS Device Address
40 Command ID (CLEAR CONFIG)
01 Payload Length (1 byte)
00 Subcommand: Clear contacts, events, and schedules
3D Checksum
C0 End Byte

Subcommand Options

Value Action Description
00 Clear all: contact configurations, events, and schedules
01 Clear only events
02 Clear only schedules (retain events)
03 Clear only contact configurations

Use the appropriate subcommand based on what part of the internal configuration needs to be cleared.

5. Request Configuration Command (0x41)

The Request Configuration command is used to query specific configurations from the WSS device, such as output settings, events, and schedules. The three payload bytes define the category, item, and configuration type being requested.

Example

00 81 41 03 00 00 01 39 C0
Byte Description
00 Host Address
81 WSS Device Address
41 Command ID (REQUEST CONFIGURATION)
03 Payload Length (3 bytes)
00 Category: Output Configuration
00 Item Index
01 Configuration Type
39 Checksum
C0 End Byte

Subcommand Payload Options

Category Item Index Config Type Description
00 00 01 Request Output Configuration List
00 01 01 Request Specific Output Configuration
01 00 01 Request Event List
01 01 01 Request Basic Event Configuration
01 02 01 Request Event Output Configuration
01 03 01 Request Event Stim Configuration
01 04 01 Request Event Shape Configuration
02 00 01 Request Schedule Basic Configuration
02 01 01 Request Schedule Listing

These subcommands allow the host to retrieve detailed system settings for output channels, event triggers, and schedule definitions.

6. Create Contact Configuration Command (0x42)

This command defines how the WSS assigns output channels (14) during stimulation and recharge phases. Each output is configured as either a source (anode), sink (cathode), or not used, and encoded into a single byte.

Example

00 81 42 03 01 11 10 17 C0
Byte Description
00 Host Address
81 WSS Device Address
42 Command ID (CREATE CONTACT CONFIGURATION)
03 Payload Length (3 bytes)
01 Contact ID
11 Stim Byte (encoded from stimulation setup)
10 Recharge Byte (encoded from recharge setup)
17 Checksum
C0 End Byte

Contact Encoding Scheme

Each output (14) is represented by 2 bits inside a single byte, arranged as follows:

[output1][output2][output3][output4]

Each output takes on one of the following values:

Value Meaning Binary
0 Not used 00
1 Source (Anode) 10
2 Sink (Cathode) 11

Example Setup

stimSetup     = [0 0 2 1];   % Output4: 0, Output3: 0, Output2: 2 (cathode), Output1: 1 (anode)
rechargeSetup = [0 0 1 2];   % Output4: 0, Output3: 0, Output2: 1 (anode), Output1: 2 (cathode)
  • Stim byte encoding:
    • Output1 (2 bits): 1 10
    • Output2: 2 11
    • Output3: 0 00
    • Output4: 0 00
    • Result: 00 00 11 10 0x11
  • Recharge byte encoding:
    • Output1: 2 11
    • Output2: 1 10
    • Output3: 0 00
    • Output4: 0 00
    • Result: 00 00 10 11 0x10

So, the encoded message body becomes:

[Contact ID] [Stim Byte] [Recharge Byte] = 01 11 10

This message tells the WSS how to activate electrode outputs during stimulation and recharge for the given contact ID.

Use this command to define safe and effective current paths in multi-electrode stimulation setups.

7. Delete Contact Configuration (0x43)

This command instructs the WSS device to delete a previously defined contact configuration, specified by its unique Contact ID.

Example

00 81 43 01 01 39 C0
Byte Description
00 Host Address
81 WSS Device Address
43 Command ID (DELETE CONTACT CONFIGURATION)
01 Payload Length (1 byte)
01 Contact ID to delete
39 Checksum
C0 End Byte

Usage Notes

  • Contact ID: Identifies which contact configuration to delete. Must match an existing ID previously created using command 0x42.
  • If the specified contact ID does not exist, the device will flag wrong ID error.

8. Create Event Command (0x44)

The Create Event command defines a stimulation event for the WSS. Each event may include different levels of configuration, from minimal to fully specified (amplitudes, pulse widths, and waveform shapes).

Minimal Payload Basic Event Definition (3 bytes)

00 81 44 03 01 02 01 33 C0
Byte Description
00 Host Address
81 WSS Device Address
44 Command ID (CREATE EVENT)
03 Payload Length (3 bytes)
01 Event ID
02 Delay (ms after schedule start)
01 Output Configuration ID
33 Checksum
C0 End Byte

Add Shape IDs (5 bytes)

00 81 44 05 01 02 01 02 00 2F C0
Byte Description
Same as above
02 Standard Shape ID
00 Recharge Shape ID
2F Checksum
C0 End Byte

Add Amplitudes and Pulse Widths (8-bit, 14 bytes total)

00 81 44 0E 01 02 01 13 13 13 13 13 13 13 13 64 32 64 94 C0
Byte Description
Same as above
134 Standard Phase Amplitudes (4 channels)
134 Recharge Phase Amplitudes (4 channels)
64 Standard Pulse Width (s)
32 IPD (Interphase Delay)
64 Recharge Pulse Width (s)
94 Checksum
C0 End Byte

16-bit Pulse Widths (17 bytes total)

00 81 44 11 01 02 01 13 13 13 13 13 13 13 13 01 32 01 32 01 64 C0
Byte Description
Same as above
01 32 Standard PW: High byte + Low byte
01 32 IPD: High byte + Low byte
01 64 Recharge PW: High byte + Low byte
C0 End Byte

Full Payload: Shapes + 16-bit Pulse Widths (19 bytes total)

00 81 44 13 01 02 01 13 13 13 13 13 13 13 13 01 32 01 32 01 64 02 00 BC C0
Byte Description
Same as 16-bit format above
02 Standard Shape ID
00 Recharge Shape ID
BC Checksum
C0 End Byte

Field Summary

Field Description
Event ID Unique identifier for the event
Delay Delay from start of schedule in milliseconds
OutConfigID Output configuration ID (refers to contact setup)
stAmp[4] 4-channel amplitudes for standard phase
reAmp[4] 4-channel amplitudes for recharge phase
PW Pulse widths: Standard, IPD, Recharge (8-bit or 16-bit)
stShape Waveform shape for standard phase
reShape Waveform shape for recharge phase

9. Delete Event Command (0x45)

The Delete Event command removes a previously created stimulation event from the WSS devices memory.

Example

00 81 45 01 01 37 C0
Byte Description
00 Host Address
81 WSS Device Address
45 Command ID (DELETE EVENT)
01 Payload Length (1 byte)
01 Event ID to delete
37 Checksum
C0 End Byte

10. Add Event to Schedule Command (0x46)

The Add Event to Schedule command assigns a previously defined event to a schedule. This links the event to be executed at a specific time based on the schedules parameters.

Example

00 81 46 02 01 02 33 C0
Byte # Byte Value Description
0 00 Host Address
1 81 WSS Device Address
2 46 Command ID (ADD EVENT TO SCHEDULE)
3 02 Payload Length (2 bytes)
4 01 Event ID
5 02 Schedule ID
6 33 Checksum
7 C0 End Byte

Field Summary

Field Description
Event ID Identifier for the event to assign to a schedule
Schedule ID Identifier of the schedule that will include this event

Ensure that both the event and schedule have already been created using 0x44 (Create Event) and 0x4A (Create Schedule) before calling this command.

11. Delete Event from Schedule Command (0x47)

The Delete Event from Schedule command removes an assigned event from a schedule. This prevents the event from being executed during the schedules activation.

Example

00 81 47 01 01 35 C0
Byte # Byte Value Description
0 00 Host Address
1 81 WSS Device Address
2 47 Command ID (DELETE EVENT FROM SCHEDULE)
3 01 Payload Length (1 byte)
4 01 Event ID to remove
5 35 Checksum
6 C0 End Byte

Field Summary

Field Description
Event ID ID of the event to be removed from its assigned schedule

Use this command when modifying a stimulation protocol dynamically or clearing a specific event without resetting the entire schedule.

12. Move Event to Schedule Command (0x48)

The Move Event to Schedule command reassigns an existing event to a new schedule and specifies a new delay time. This is useful when dynamically updating stimulation timing without recreating the event.

Example

00 81 48 03 01 02 01 2F C0
Byte # Byte Value Description
0 00 Host Address
1 81 WSS Device Address
2 48 Command ID (MOVE EVENT TO SCHEDULE)
3 03 Payload Length (3 bytes)
4 01 Event ID
5 02 Schedule ID
6 01 Delay (ms) from schedule start
7 2F Checksum
8 C0 End Byte

Field Summary

Field Description
Event ID Identifier of the event to be moved
Schedule ID Identifier of the new schedule to assign the event to
Delay New delay (in milliseconds) from the start of the schedule

Use this command when refining or re-timing event sequences in a stimulation protocol.

13. Edit Event Command (0x49)

The Edit Event command allows modification of specific properties of a previously created event. The subcommand (cmd) specifies which parameter will be editedsuch as output configuration, pulse widths, amplitudes, shapes, delay, or ratio.

Subcommand Variants

Change Output Configuration

00 81 49 03 01 01 02 2E C0
Byte # Byte Value Description
03 Host, WSS Address, Command ID, Payload Len
4 01 Event ID
5 01 Subcommand: Change Output Configuration
6 02 Output Configuration ID
78 Checksum, End Byte

Edit Pulse Width Timings (8-bit resolution)

00 81 49 05 01 02 64 32 64 32 C0
Byte # Byte Value Description
4 01 Event ID
5 02 Subcommand: Edit Pulse Widths (8-bit)
6 64 Standard Pulse Width (s)
7 32 Interphase Delay (s)
8 64 Recharge Pulse Width (s)

Edit Pulse Width Timings (16-bit resolution)

00 81 49 08 01 03 01 32 01 32 01 64 5D C0

Note: 16-bit values are split into High Byte and Low Byte, encoded in Big Endian format (High byte first).

Byte # Byte Value Description
4 01 Event ID
5 03 Subcommand: Edit PW (16-bit)
67 01 32 Standard PW 0x0132 = 306 s
89 01 32 IPD 0x0132 = 306 s
1011 01 64 Recharge PW 0x0164 = 356 s

Byte Division:
- 16-bit value = High Byte 256 + Low Byte
- Example: 0x01 0x32 1256 + 50 = 306 s

Edit Pulse Amplitudes

00 81 49 0A 01 04 13 13 13 13 13 13 13 13 8D C0
Byte # Byte Value Description
4 01 Event ID
5 04 Subcommand: Edit Pulse Amplitudes
69 13 13 13 13 Standard Amplitudes (4 outputs)
1013 13 13 13 13 Recharge Amplitudes (4 outputs)

Edit Pulse Shapes

00 81 49 04 01 05 02 00 29 C0
Byte # Byte Value Description
4 01 Event ID
5 05 Subcommand: Edit Pulse Shapes
6 02 Standard Shape ID
7 00 Recharge Shape ID

Edit Delay (8-bit)

00 81 49 03 01 06 02 29 C0
Byte # Byte Value Description
4 01 Event ID
5 06 Subcommand: Edit Delay
6 02 Delay from schedule start (ms)

Edit Ratio

00 81 49 03 01 07 04 26 C0
Byte # Byte Value Description
4 01 Event ID
5 07 Subcommand: Edit Ratio
6 04 Ratio value (unitless)

Subcommand Summary

cmd Description Notes
01 Change Output Configuration Set a new output config ID
02 Edit Pulse Widths (8-bit) PW, IPD, RPW all in s
03 Edit Pulse Widths (16-bit) Uses High/Low byte encoding
04 Edit Pulse Amplitudes 4 standard + 4 recharge outputs
05 Edit Pulse Shapes Shape ID for stim and recharge
06 Edit Delay from Schedule Start 8-bit delay in ms
07 Edit Event Ratio Modulation ratio, if supported

14. Create Schedule Command (0x4A)

The Create Schedule command defines a new stimulation schedule in the WSS device. Each schedule is assigned a unique ID and a fixed duration (in milliseconds). An optional synchronization signal (syncSig) can be specified to trigger and synchronize the schedules.

Example

00 81 4A 04 01 00 20 AA 64 C0
Byte # Byte Value Description
0 00 Host Address
1 81 WSS Device Address
2 4A Command ID (CREATE SCHEDULE)
3 04 Payload Length (4 bytes)
4 01 Schedule ID
5 00 High Byte of Schedule Duration
6 20 Low Byte of Schedule Duration (0x0020 = 32 ms)
7 AA Sync Signal ID (for triggering or grouping)
8 64 Checksum
9 C0 End Byte

Duration Example:
High Byte: 0x00
Low Byte: 0x20
Total Duration = 0x0020 = 32 ms

15. Delete Schedule (0x4B)

The Delete Schedule command removes a schedule from the devices schedule array.

Example

00 81 4B 01 01 31 C0
Byte # Byte Value Description
0 00 Host Address
1 81 WSS Device Address
2 4B Command ID (DELETE SCHEDULE)
3 01 Payload Length (1 byte)
4 01 Schedule ID to delete
5 31 Checksum
6 C0 End Byte

16. Schedule Group Sync Command (0x4C)

The Schedule Group Sync command simultaneously starts all schedules that share a specified synchronization signal. It resets the timing of these schedules and activates them together as a group.

Example

00 81 4C 01 AA 86 C0
Byte # Byte Value Description
0 00 Host Address
1 81 WSS Device Address
2 4C Command ID (SCHEDULE GROUP SYNC)
3 01 Payload Length (1 byte)
4 AA Sync Signal ID
5 86 Checksum
6 C0 End Byte

Use this command to trigger coordinated stimulation across multiple schedules configured with the same sync signal (see 0x4A Create Schedule command).
